WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:07.220 --> 00:00:10.559
Hey, Vsauce. Michael here. I am

00:00:10.559 --> 00:00:13.960
distorted. The pixels you are watching have been

00:00:13.960 --> 00:00:18.180
time displaced. They've been mapped onto a gradient

00:00:18.180 --> 00:00:21.779
and the darker the region they're mapped to,
the further behind

00:00:21.779 --> 00:00:25.590
they lag. The effect is really fun but it's certainly

00:00:25.590 --> 00:00:28.590
not realistic. Or is it?

00:00:31.230 --> 00:00:35.820
Many, many popular digital cameras suffer
from lag induced distortion,

00:00:35.820 --> 00:00:39.020
like what you just saw, though much,

00:00:39.020 --> 00:00:42.460
much more subtle. Usually completely

00:00:42.460 --> 00:00:45.710
unnoticeable. It's called a rolling shutter.

00:00:45.710 --> 00:00:48.790
Instead of snapping a full exposure at once

00:00:48.790 --> 00:00:52.199
they quickly scan strips of each frame. It's

00:00:52.199 --> 00:00:56.710
usually undetectable. But when the
subject changes faster than the camera

00:00:56.710 --> 00:00:57.550
scans,

00:00:57.550 --> 00:01:03.210
you get the famous geloey wobbly rolling 
shutter effect. Really fast

00:01:03.210 --> 00:01:06.800
things, like vibrating guitar strings and
airplane propellers,

00:01:06.800 --> 00:01:11.710
are famous victims, but people can be too.
Luke Mandel submitted this photo

00:01:11.710 --> 00:01:16.619
to Boing Boing[.net]. His camera scans left to
right and, in this instance,

00:01:16.619 --> 00:01:20.210
managed to capture a blink, eyes closed

00:01:20.210 --> 00:01:25.170
when the scan began and then open in the
reflection scanned a fraction

00:01:25.170 --> 00:01:28.740
of a second later.
But the rolling shutter effect

00:01:28.740 --> 00:01:32.700
is not just a neat curiosity. It represents

00:01:32.700 --> 00:01:36.130
a fundamental and inescapable distortion that

00:01:36.130 --> 00:01:39.710
affects everything we see. Rolling shutter

00:01:39.710 --> 00:01:44.119
or not. First things first, let's talk about distortions.

00:01:44.119 --> 00:01:47.409
A hallucination is a distortion of reality

00:01:47.409 --> 00:01:51.390
when there is no apparent stimulus. If you are merely

00:01:51.390 --> 00:01:55.700
misinterpreting an actual stimulus, that is an illusion.

00:01:55.700 --> 00:01:59.909
But some distortions occur before our sense organs

00:01:59.909 --> 00:02:03.180
and minds get in the way. They are called

00:02:03.180 --> 00:02:08.340
optical phenomena. They are not the
result of sensation or perception gone wrong.

00:02:08.340 --> 00:02:13.660
Instead, optical phenomena are distortions
caused by the mere properties of light

00:02:13.660 --> 00:02:14.500
and matter

00:02:14.500 --> 00:02:17.970
in and of themselves. If you look up at the sky

00:02:17.970 --> 00:02:21.640
and see a giant vivid drinking gourd,

00:02:21.640 --> 00:02:24.900
you are hallucinating. But if you see a flat

00:02:24.900 --> 00:02:29.000
two-dimensional connect-the-dots
Big Dipper, you are seeing

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:32.290
an illusion. It's an illusion because those dots merely

00:02:32.290 --> 00:02:37.510
appear to be on the same plane, like
holes poked in the dark roof of the sky.

00:02:37.510 --> 00:02:40.609
In reality, those dots are stars

00:02:40.609 --> 00:02:44.730
lightyears apart from one another in three dimensions.

00:02:44.730 --> 00:02:48.840
As Celestron's brilliant free real-time
3D visualization of space

00:02:48.840 --> 00:02:52.440
shows, from different perspectives, besides our own,

00:02:52.440 --> 00:02:56.410
they look a lot less like a dipper or plough.

00:02:56.410 --> 00:02:59.660
In fact, all constellations and asterisms

00:02:59.660 --> 00:03:03.650
are geocentric illusions. From a wider perspective

00:03:03.650 --> 00:03:06.730
their outlines point inward,

00:03:06.730 --> 00:03:09.790
to the single lowly point in space

00:03:09.790 --> 00:03:13.560
that gave them their names. But you can't blame us.

00:03:13.560 --> 00:03:18.400
I mean, Earth is the only perspective any
human has ever had.

00:03:18.420 --> 00:03:22.200
And even Voyager 1,
the most distant man-made object,

00:03:22.209 --> 00:03:26.060
is still not even close to being far
enough away for the constellations to look

00:03:26.060 --> 00:03:29.760
even remotely different than they do here on Earth.

00:03:29.760 --> 00:03:33.570
It's also not our fault, our eyes' and brains'

00:03:33.570 --> 00:03:37.109
fault, that distant, distant stars weren't included

00:03:37.109 --> 00:03:40.810
in our early cosmic connect-the-dot game.

00:03:40.810 --> 00:03:44.079
Sure, our eyesight could be better,

00:03:44.079 --> 00:03:47.130
but optical phenomena are also to blame.

00:03:47.130 --> 00:03:52.350
If it weren't for red shifting and the
inverse square law and light extinction,

00:03:52.350 --> 00:03:55.600
distant things could be seen in all their glory.

00:03:55.600 --> 00:03:59.820
The night sky would look phenomenal. Many structures

00:03:59.820 --> 00:04:03.150
up there are huge. They're just

00:04:03.150 --> 00:04:06.850
too dim for their hugeness to be appreciated.

00:04:06.850 --> 00:04:11.870
When we see Hubble Telescope images of
distant objects, like the Helix Nebula,

00:04:11.870 --> 00:04:15.510
it's easy to think that, without a telescope to zoom in,

00:04:15.510 --> 00:04:19.290
the object must just be a tiny point in the sky.

00:04:19.290 --> 00:04:23.419
But in reality, even though the Helix Nebula is

00:04:23.419 --> 00:04:26.680
700 light years away, it's

00:04:26.680 --> 00:04:31.160
3 lightyears across. If we could make the Helix Nebula

00:04:31.160 --> 00:04:34.340
less dim, if our eyes could take a

00:04:34.340 --> 00:04:37.729
really long exposure of it,
we would see the Helix Nebula

00:04:37.729 --> 00:04:42.840
as it really is - nearly 70% the apparent diameter

00:04:42.840 --> 00:04:47.380
of our Moon. This is a serious picture.
That is how large

00:04:47.380 --> 00:04:50.800
the Helix Nebula would appear in the
night sky from Earth

00:04:50.800 --> 00:04:54.360
if it just wasn't so dim. Our Moon is

00:04:54.360 --> 00:04:59.200
tiny in the sky, by the way. It's easy to
think of the moon as this huge

00:04:59.200 --> 00:05:02.910
baseball-sized thing up there in the sky,
but that's an illusion.

00:05:02.910 --> 00:05:06.960
Try this the next time you see the
Moon. Grab a sheet of notebook paper

00:05:06.960 --> 00:05:10.300
and you will notice that the angular
diameter of the Moon

00:05:10.300 --> 00:05:14.840
is the same size as a hole punched in a
sheet of notebook paper held

00:05:14.840 --> 00:05:19.880
in arms-length away. Seriously, try it
sometime. It shows just how

00:05:19.880 --> 00:05:23.620
cute and tiny our little moon is.
The Orion Nebula

00:05:23.620 --> 00:05:27.100
would appear even larger, if we saw all of its light.

00:05:27.100 --> 00:05:30.180
And the Andromeda Galaxy? Just

00:05:30.180 --> 00:05:34.970
a smudge in the sky to our eyes. But if our
eyes were better at collecting

00:05:34.970 --> 00:05:38.420
dim light, we would see Andromeda's true extent

00:05:38.420 --> 00:05:41.690
in our sky. Of course, our

00:05:41.690 --> 00:05:44.720
night sky doesn't look like that. Distant objects

00:05:44.720 --> 00:05:49.520
are dimmer, that's a bummer. But light still
wins when it comes to speed.

00:05:49.520 --> 00:05:55.320
Light travels at the fastest speed.
In fact, in a vacuum, light travels

00:05:55.330 --> 00:05:57.970
300,000 kilometres a second.

00:05:58.540 --> 00:05:59.400
That's fast.

