00:07:20.290 --> 00:07:25.960
The Andromeda Galaxy is huge. It's more
than a hundred thousand light years across

00:07:25.960 --> 00:07:29.590
and our view of it is tilted.

00:07:29.590 --> 00:07:33.820
Which means that, on the plane we view it in,
light from the back

00:07:33.820 --> 00:07:39.240
represents what Andromeda looked like
thousands and thousands of years before

00:07:39.240 --> 00:07:42.330
what light from the front represents.

00:07:42.330 --> 00:07:45.690
Changes in its appearance reach us 
sooner from the front

00:07:45.690 --> 00:07:50.270
than from the back. Andromeda is rotating,
spinning at hundreds of kilometers per

00:07:50.270 --> 00:07:51.910
second in some places.

00:07:51.910 --> 00:07:55.670
Now, a lag between light coming from near

00:07:55.670 --> 00:07:58.880
and far points on a spinning object, results

00:07:58.880 --> 00:08:03.690
in a skewed image. The rolling shutter
effect on a cosmic scale

00:08:03.690 --> 00:08:06.700
applied to, say, a chessboard, seeing the front

00:08:06.700 --> 00:08:10.410
ahead of the back is pretty trippy and dramatic.

00:08:11.260 --> 00:08:13.780
So, does that mean we see

00:08:13.790 --> 00:08:18.200
wobbly, funhouse mirror, rolling
shutter effect versions of Andromeda

00:08:18.200 --> 00:08:21.670
and other distant galaxies? Well, technically

00:08:21.670 --> 00:08:26.660
yeah, but the distortion is negligible. It may as well be

00:08:26.660 --> 00:08:30.020
ignored. Why? Well,

00:08:30.020 --> 00:08:33.670
the speeds used in these visualizations are not

00:08:33.670 --> 00:08:38.250
to scale. On average, yes, matter within galaxies

00:08:38.250 --> 00:08:41.700
orbits the galactic center at hundreds
of kilometers per second

00:08:41.700 --> 00:08:45.560
but galaxies are so huge it takes them

00:08:45.560 --> 00:08:49.210
hundreds of millions of years to complete just one

00:08:49.210 --> 00:08:53.740
rotation. In other words, the lag between light

00:08:53.740 --> 00:08:57.000
reaching you from near and far points on a galaxy,

00:08:57.000 --> 00:09:00.290
is nothing compared to how much time it takes

00:09:00.290 --> 00:09:03.860
matter in the galaxy to travel that same distance.

00:09:03.860 --> 00:09:06.990
In the case of Andromeda, if you insisted

00:09:06.990 --> 00:09:10.380
on seeing Andromeda as it really is,

00:09:10.380 --> 00:09:15.560
that is, corrected for any lag caused by
the fact that the speed of light is

00:09:15.560 --> 00:09:18.800
finite, the most extreme points on the Galaxy

00:09:18.800 --> 00:09:23.040
would only need to be adjusted by about a 10,000th of

00:09:23.040 --> 00:09:26.420
the width of any image. In this case, less than a pixel.

00:09:26.420 --> 00:09:30.800
So, it's not a big deal. But it's not a nothing deal.

00:09:30.800 --> 00:09:34.530
It's real. In fact, everything we look at is,

00:09:34.530 --> 00:09:37.670
in some way, distorted by the fact that the speed of light

00:09:37.670 --> 00:09:40.750
is finite. Your own feet are about

00:09:40.750 --> 00:09:47.140
5 to 6 light nano seconds away from your
eyes, which means when you look at your feet

00:09:47.140 --> 00:09:50.950
